{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778304769,"nonce":"XzypYZxVccwGYC0E+Z1EBDuzxj8=","message":"**Addendum: pre-target-on epoch is unique to our task and probably superfluous.**\n\nDirect read of Shahbazi 2025 §4.2 (savings paper Methods, p. 16) confirms they have NO separate pre-target-on hold epoch. The target signal is on from trial start; what changes at the go-cue is the desired position in the loss:\n\n\u003e \"The desired position was set to be equal to the starting position of the limb endpoint before the go cue, and after that the target position.\"\n\n\u003e \"In the other 50% of cases the time of the go-cue switch from 0 to 1 was drawn from a random uniform distribution between 100 ms and 300 ms after the start of each simulated trial.\"\n\nSo in their structure, t=0 is when the trial starts AND the target signal is on; the network just has to hold position until the go-cue switches.\n\nComparison:\n| Phase | Ours | Shahbazi 2025 |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pre-target hold (target NOT shown) | 10 steps fixed (100 ms) | none |\n| Target-on, pre-go (target shown, hold ON) | 5–20 steps random (50–200 ms) | 10–30 steps random (100–300 ms) |\n| Movement (post-go) | n_steps − above | up to 1 s total |\n\n**Two task-side intervention sub-strategies for strategy 5 (preparation-duration adjustment):**\n\n5a. **Drop the 10-step pure-hold epoch** — set `epoch_len_ranges[0] = [0, 1]` (or remove entirely). Target on from trial start. Aligns with Shahbazi/MotorNet convention.\n\n5b. **Bump target-on window** to `[10, 30]` (100–300 ms) — matches Shahbazi exactly, also covers the 150–300 ms monkey-prep range.\n\nBoth are config-only, small/zero net BPTT cost when bundled (5a frees up 10 steps that 5b reuses). Should likely be tested together, listed as strategy 5 in the matrix.","files":null}]}